\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

A \emph{clique edge-partition} (CEP) of a graph $G=(V,E)$ is a collection
$\{Q_1,\dots,Q_t\}$ of complete subgraphs of $G$ whose edge sets partition
$E(G)$.  Write $\cp(G)$ for the minimum $t$.  Two cliques in any CEP share
at most one vertex (sharing two would share an edge, contradicting partition).

A graph is \emph{chordal} if every induced cycle has length exactly~$3$;
equivalently, it admits a \emph{perfect elimination ordering} (PEO), a
linear ordering $v_1,\dots,v_n$ such that $\Nplus(v_i):=N(v_i)\cap\{v_{i+1},\dots,v_n\}$
is a clique for every $i$.

\subsection*{Summary of results}

We study $f(n):=\max\{\cp(G):G\text{ chordal on }n\text{ vertices}\}$.  The
extremal family (\cref{sec:lower}) shows $f(n)\ge n^2/6-O(n)$, and more
precisely $f(3m)\ge(3m)^2/6+(3m)/6$ for every $m\ge 1$.  The
unconditional upper bound (\cref{sec:upper}) gives $f(n)\le n^2/4+O(n)$.
One sufficient condition for obtaining the $n^2/6+O(n)$ bound is
isolated and proved (\cref{sec:conditional}).  Since this condition
fails for the extremal split graphs, a different argument is needed
for the full problem.

