\section{Failed Approaches to the Upper Bound}
\label{sec:failed}

We document two earlier attempted proofs of the $n^2/6$ bound and the
precise reason each fails.

\subsection{Triangle--Forest partition (false)}

\noindent\textbf{Claimed.} Every chordal graph admits a partition of $E(G)$
into edge-disjoint triangles and a forest.

\begin{example}[$K_5$ is a counterexample]
$K_5$ is chordal with $m=10$ edges.  Any forest on $5$ vertices has $\le 4$
edges, so at least $2$ triangles are needed.  Two edge-disjoint triangles in
$K_5$ share one vertex (say $\{a,b,c\}$ and $\{a,d,e\}$); the $4$ remaining
edges $\{bd,be,cd,ce\}$ form a $4$-cycle, not a forest.  Three
edge-disjoint triangles are impossible: their union would have $9$ edges, but
$K_5$ minus one edge has two odd-degree vertices while any union of triangles
has all even degrees.
\end{example}

The inductive proof of this claimed lemma erred at the step: ``adding star
edges from a new vertex $v$ to an existing forest $R'$ cannot create a
cycle.''  If $v$ is joined to two vertices in the same component of $R'$,
the path between them together with the two new $v$-edges creates a cycle.

\subsection{PEO triangle-packing algorithm (flawed bookkeeping)}

A PEO-based algorithm was proposed: at step $i$, match pairs within
$R_i=\{v_k\in\Nplus(v_i): v_iv_k\notin\mathrm{PRECOV}\}$ using only
free within-pair edges, forming triangles and pre-covering their mutual
edges.

\begin{example}[$K_4$ breaks the key inequality]
With PEO $v_1,v_2,v_3,v_4$: at step~$1$ match $\{v_3,v_4\}$, forming
$\{v_1,v_3,v_4\}$ and pre-covering $v_3v_4$.  At step~$2$, $R_2=\{v_3,v_4\}$
but the only within-$R_2$ edge ($v_3v_4$) is pre-covered, so $|M_2|=0$.
Triangle count $T=1$.  The claimed bound $T\ge(m-n)/3=(6-4)/3=0.67$ holds
for $K_4$, but for $G_3=\Sp(K_3,I_6)$ the algorithm yields $T=3$ while
$(m-n)/3=(21-9)/3=4>3$.  Moreover, the bound $\cp(G)\le m/3+2n/3$ claimed
from this approach gives $7+6=13$ for $G_3$, but $\cp(G_3)=15>13$.
\end{example}

